    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-12-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-12-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="327"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.5914/49½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-12-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">5 December, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I am glad the Danish Minister
                    gave you an opportunity to be so frank with him, and I hope he realizes how
                    entirely friendly to Denmark the frankness was. It would appear from the
                    enclosed message from the Danish Minister of Foreign Affairs<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d327fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_502">p. 502</ref>.</note> that
                    he does.</p>
                <p>I hope that you will do as you suggest, namely, first ascertain just what is
                    meant by the occupation of Greenland and, should that matter be satisfactorily
                    cleared up, proceed at once to the negotiation of a treaty for the purchase of
                    the Danish West Indies. The opportunity <pb facs="0551" n="505" xml:id="pg_505"
                    /> has apparently come, and we may be able to relieve the Danish Government of a
                    considerable embarrassment.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
